raucous protest. Taiwanese unions are seen as moderate and practical, primarily working through formal political processes to lobby their agendas. In exploring how and why these post-democratization states have come to breed such different types of labor politics, Yoonkyung Lee traces the roots of their differences to how unions and political parties operated under authoritarianism, and points to ways in which those legacies continue to be perpetuated. By pairing two cases with many similarities, Lee persuasively uncovers factors that explain the significant variation at play.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDemocracyxKorea (South). 0aDemocracyxTaiwan. 0aDemocracyzKorea (South). 0aDemocracyzTaiwan. 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityxKorea (South). 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityxTaiwan. 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzKorea (South). 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzTaiwan. 0aPolitical science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804781749zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804781749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804781749.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles